he Frankfurt School—Veronika Fuechtner traces the network of artists and psychoanalysts that began in Germany and continued in exile. Connecting movements, forms, and themes such as Dada, multi-perspectivity, and the urban experience with the theory and practice of psychoanalysis, she illuminates themes distinctive to the Berlin psychoanalytic context such as war trauma, masculinity and femininity, race and anti-Semitism, and the cultural avant-garde. In particular, she explores the lives and works of Alfred Döblin, Max Eitingon, Georg Groddeck, Karen Horney, Richard Huelsenbeck, Count Hermann von Keyserling, Ernst Simmel, and Arnold Zweig.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aArtistszGermanyzBerlinvBiography. 0aAuthors, GermanzGermanyzBerlinvBiography. 0aModernism (Aesthetics)zGermanyzBerlinxHistoryy20th century. 0aPsychoanalysis and culturezGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 0aPsychoanalysis and culturezNew York (State)zNew YorkxHistoryy20th century. 0aPsychoanalysis and culturezPalestinexHistoryy20th century. 0aPsychoanalystszGermanyzBerlinvBiography. 7aHISTORY / Europe / General.2bisacsh  a20th century germany.  a20th century mental health.  aalfred doblin.  aarnold zweig.  acount hermann von keyserling.  acultural avant-garde.  aernst simmel.  aeuropean history.  ageorg groddeck.  agerman history.  agerman scientists.  ahistory of psychoanalysis.  ahistory of psychology.  akaren horney.  akarl abraham.  amasculinity and femininity.  amax eitingon.  amedical psychoanalysis.  amental health and psychoanalysis.  apsychoanalysis.  apsychology psychoanalysis.  apsychotherapy.  arace and anti-semitism.  arichard huelsenbeck.  awar trauma.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013